certainly the annulment by the Federation International de Football Association (FIFA) of the 2010/2011 and 2011/2012 seasons’ Cameroonian Football League, for the 2010/2011 season’s final table had, according to the FIFA ruling, great irregularities, and that the results of some teams’ games had been tampered with. Matters were further exacerbated by the transfer of the same official who presided over the said game to England’s premier league and beautifying FIFA’s prestigious reputation as a regulatory body with ultimate power of control over a legally functioning NOC, while Cameroon’s football Prime Minister, Dilbert Ekane, got less conniving, vinegar in the bowels, a cold of his sort. The annulment was a huge blow to the prestige and pride of the National soccer team, Les Lions indomptables; a huge blow indeed, but more importantly, it was a trip hither from greatness to ordinary.

For instance, among other disgusting features which informed the UNESCO’S selection of Cameroon as a beneficiary of its capacity building project on anti-doping and climate change action projects, is the fact the percentage of African Footballers doping in the African continent tripled from 6 to 18% in the 2011 PREMIER TEST conducted by the East African Gambling Commission.
